and Japanese scholarship. These include the rise of new literary and artistic values as the Han declined, changing patterns of patronage that helped reshape literary tastes and genres, and new developments in literary criticism. The religious changes of the period are revealed in the literary self-presentation of spiritual seekers, the influence of Daoism on motifs in poetry, and Buddhist influences on both poetry and historiography. Traditional Chinese literary figures, such as the fox and the ghost, receive fresh analysis about their particular representation during this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChinese literaturexExplication. 0aChinese literaturexPhilosophy. 0aChinese literaturey220-589xHistory and criticism. 0aHermeneutics. 0aPhilosophy in literature. 0aReligion and literaturezChinaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aHistory : History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aCai, Zong-Qi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampany, Robert Ford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Alan K. L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChan, Timothy Wai-Keung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChennault, Cynthia L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsieh, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnechtges, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLo, Yuet-Keung, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNylan, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoo, Mu-Chou, eco